{
  "Why is it impossible to perfectly represent Earth's surface on a flat map?": "",
  "Earth's surface is constantly changing": "",
  "There are not enough satellites to map the entire Earth": "",
  "Transferring a three-dimensional sphere to a two-dimensional surface always introduces distortion": "",
  "Map-making technology is not advanced enough": "",
  "It is mathematically impossible to represent a spherical surface on a flat plane without distorting at least one property: shape, area, distance, or direction. Every map projection involves trade-offs between these properties.": "",
  "What does the Mercator projection preserve?": "",
  "Shape and direction (angles), making it useful for navigation": "",
  "The relative size of continents": "",
  "Accurate area of all landmasses": "",
  "Distance between all points": "",
  "The Mercator projection is conformal, preserving shapes and angles, which makes it ideal for navigation because a straight line on the map represents a constant compass bearing. However, it greatly distorts the size of areas near the poles.": "",
  "What is the major distortion problem with the Mercator projection?": "",
  "It cannot show the Southern Hemisphere": "",
  "It greatly exaggerates the size of landmasses near the poles, making Greenland appear as large as Africa": "",
  "It makes Africa appear too large": "",
  "It distorts the shape of all continents": "",
  "The Mercator projection increasingly stretches areas toward the poles. Greenland appears similar in size to Africa, when in reality Africa is about 14 times larger, leading to misconceptions about the relative sizes of countries.": "",
  "What does the Robinson projection attempt to do?": "",
  "Perfectly preserve both shape and area": "",
  "Eliminate all distortion from maps": "",
  "Show only the Western Hemisphere": "",
  "Compromise between distortions to create a visually balanced world map": "",
  "The Robinson projection is a compromise projection that does not perfectly preserve any single property but minimizes distortion across the map, creating a visually appealing and relatively accurate world map used commonly in textbooks.": "",
  "What property does an equal-area (equivalent) projection preserve?": "",
  "The correct shape of all landmasses": "",
  "True compass directions from any point": "",
  "Accurate distances between all points": "",
  "The correct relative size (area) of all landmasses": "",
  "Equal-area projections maintain correct proportional sizes of all areas on the map, so the relative sizes of countries and continents are accurately represented. However, this comes at the cost of distorting shapes.": "",
  "What are the four properties that map projections can distort?": "",
  "Scale, resolution, accuracy, and precision": "",
  "Latitude, longitude, altitude, and time": "",
  "Color, texture, height, and depth": "",
  "Shape, area, distance, and direction": "",
  "Every flat map distorts at least one of four properties: shape (conformal projections preserve this), area (equal-area projections preserve this), distance (equidistant projections preserve this), and direction (azimuthal projections preserve this).": "",
  "What type of map uses shading or color patterns to show the density or intensity of a variable within predefined areas?": "",
  "Topographic map": "",
  "Dot density map": "",
  "Choropleth map": "",
  "Cartogram": "",
  "A choropleth map uses colors or shading of predefined areas (countries, states, counties) to represent the intensity of a variable, such as population density, income levels, or election results.": "",
  "What is a thematic map?": "",
  "A map used exclusively for navigation": "",
  "A map designed to display a particular theme or subject, such as population, climate, or economic activity": "",
  "A map showing all possible information about an area": "",
  "A map that shows only physical features like mountains and rivers": "",
  "Thematic maps focus on displaying specific topics or themes, such as population distribution, disease prevalence, or election results, using specialized symbolization techniques like choropleth shading, dot density, or proportional symbols.": "",
  "What is a cartogram?": "",
  "An ancient map drawn on parchment according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "A telegram sent using a map as a code, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "A map where the size of geographic areas is distorted to be proportional to a statistical variable like population": "",
  "A small-scale map of a local area when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "A cartogram distorts the size of geographic units (countries, states) to make them proportional to a variable being mapped, such as population or GDP. For example, India would appear much larger than Canada on a population cartogram.": "",
  "What is the difference between a large-scale map and a small-scale map?": "",
  "Large-scale maps show a small area in great detail, while small-scale maps show a large area with less detail": "",
  "Large-scale maps are always printed on large paper": "",
  "Large-scale maps show large areas while small-scale maps show small areas": "",
  "There is no meaningful difference between them": "",
  "Large-scale maps (e.g., 1:10,000) show a small geographic area with great detail, like a neighborhood. Small-scale maps (e.g., 1:10,000,000) show large areas like countries or continents with less detail.": "",
  "What is a 'map projection'?": "",
  "A systematic method of transferring locations from Earth's curved surface onto a flat map": "",
  "A device that projects map images onto a screen": "",
  "The shadow cast by Earth's features on a flat surface": "",
  "A prediction of how maps will look in the future": "",
  "A map projection is a mathematical method for representing Earth's three-dimensional surface on a two-dimensional map. Each projection has a specific set of trade-offs regarding which properties are preserved and which are distorted.": "",
  "What does 'conformal projection' mean?": "",
  "A map projection that preserves local shapes and angles at the expense of area distortion": "",
  "A projection used only for political maps": "",
  "A projection that makes all maps look the same": "",
  "A projection that conforms to international mapping standards": "",
  "A conformal projection preserves local shapes and angles, meaning small features look correct. The Mercator projection is conformal, making it useful for navigation, but it distorts the size of large areas, especially near the poles.": "",
  "What does 'equal-area projection' mean?": "",
  "A projection where all countries appear the same size": "",
  "A projection used to measure the area of buildings": "",
  "A projection that gives equal space to every continent": "",
  "A map projection that correctly represents the relative sizes of areas on Earth's surface": "",
  "An equal-area (equivalent) projection maintains the correct proportional sizes of all mapped areas. If Africa is 14 times larger than Greenland in reality, it will appear 14 times larger on the map, though shapes may be distorted.": "",
  "What is a 'reference map'?": "",
