  "A map showing the locations of polka-dot fabric stores": "",
  "A random pattern of dots placed on a map": "",
  "A thematic map that uses dots to represent the spatial distribution and density of a phenomenon": "",
  "A dot distribution (dot density) map places dots on a map where each dot represents a specific quantity of the mapped variable. The pattern of dots shows where the phenomenon is concentrated or sparse.": "",
  "What is 'distortion' on a map?": "",
  "Damage to a map from folding or water": "",
  "Intentional errors added to maps for copyright protection": "",
  "The unavoidable alteration of shape, area, distance, or direction when representing Earth's curved surface on a flat map": "",
  "Inaccuracies caused by outdated data": "",
  "Map distortion is the unavoidable alteration that occurs when transferring information from a sphere to a flat surface. No flat map can simultaneously preserve shape, area, distance, and direction perfectly.": "",
  "What does 'azimuthal projection' mean?": "",
  "A projection that preserves direction from a central point, projecting the globe onto a flat plane touching it at one point": "",
  "A projection based on the direction of the sun": "",
  "A three-dimensional map projection": "",
  "A projection used only for maps of the Middle East": "",
  "An azimuthal projection projects the globe onto a flat plane, preserving direction (and sometimes distance) from a central point. It is commonly used for polar maps and flight route planning from a specific location.": "",
  "What is a 'proportional symbol map'?": "",
  "A map where all symbols are the same size": "",
  "A thematic map that uses symbols of varying sizes to represent different quantities at specific locations": "",
  "A map where territory size is proportional to a variable": "",
  "A map that uses symbols instead of words for the legend": "",
  "A proportional symbol map uses symbols (usually circles) of different sizes placed at specific locations to represent the magnitude of a variable, such as city population size or earthquake magnitude.": "",
  "What is 'latitude'?": "",
  "The height of land above sea level": "",
  "Angular distance measured north or south of the equator, expressed in degrees": "",
  "Lines running north-south from pole to pole": "",
  "The distance between two cities": "",
  "Latitude measures angular distance north or south of the equator in degrees (0° at equator, 90° at poles). Lines of latitude (parallels) run east-west and are used to describe a location's position between the equator and the poles.": "",
  "What is 'longitude'?": "",
  "Lines running east-west around the globe": "",
  "The length of time it takes to travel between two places": "",
