  "A student looking at a Mercator projection map concludes that Greenland is roughly the same size as Africa. When shown a Peters (equal-area) projection, Africa appears much larger. Which map shows the correct size relationship, and why do these maps differ?": "",
  "The Peters projection correctly shows Africa's much larger size because equal-area projections preserve relative area, while Mercator's conformal projection distorts area near the poles": "",
  "The Mercator map is correct because it is more commonly used according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Both maps are equally correct in showing size because the underlying forces at work tend to produce exactly this type of outcome": "",
  "Neither map shows accurate sizes, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "Africa (30.4 million km²) is about 14 times larger than Greenland (2.2 million km²). The Peters equal-area projection correctly shows this difference, while the Mercator greatly inflates high-latitude areas, making Greenland appear disproportionately large.": "",
  "An airline pilot needs to determine the shortest flight path from New York to Tokyo. On a Mercator map, a straight line appears to go directly across the Atlantic and Europe. However, the actual shortest route flies over the Arctic. Why does the map mislead?": "",
  "The map is drawn incorrectly": "",
  "The pilot should always follow straight lines on maps": "",
  "Straight lines on all maps represent the shortest distance": "",
  "The Mercator projection distorts distances, and the shortest path on a sphere (great circle route) appears curved on a flat map": "",
  "On a globe, the shortest path between two points follows a great circle (part of a circle with the same center as Earth). On a Mercator map, great circle routes appear as curves, while straight lines (rhumb lines) are actually longer routes.": "",
  "A political scientist creates a world cartogram where country sizes are proportional to GDP rather than land area. On this map, Japan appears much larger than usual while Russia appears much smaller. What does this type of map effectively communicate?": "",
